<div id="content" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<a href="./RavenRed">RavenRed</a>: Has anyone here ever had repeated quests for the same monster? You just finish the FF quest for 19 Trappers and then two levels later you get another FF Quest for 16 Trappers.... and you still don't have See Invisible... not that it would be a lot of help if you did... This has happened quite a few times, with various monsters and I'm just wondering whether the RNG is being especially cruel or if there's something in the code that's too lazy to think of a new monster every time... <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/smile4.png" alt=";-)" height="15" width="15"> <p>
My bet is on RNG sadism. Ohhhh no... ANOTHER quest for Greater Draconic Qulthyugs... &lt;sigh&gt; Can't FF lose his Sword to some nice easy Water Hounds or something?  
</p>
<p>
<img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/smile.png" alt=":-)" height="15" width="15"> 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a>: Greater Draconic Qs are among my most favorite monsters in the whole game.  I'd feel lucky to run into them over and over! 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./RavenRed">RavenRed</a>: &lt;shudder&gt; You sure you're not Lord Dimwit? You're showing a frightening degree of masochism...  
</p>
<p>
<a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a>:  Not masochism, just a tendency to have four immunities by the time I run into them.  You won't see me stay long on a level with other Greater Qs. It's just the Draconic ones that I like to fight for hours and collect thousands of items from. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./RavenRed">RavenRed</a>: Oh... for Farming purposes, fair enough... I wonder if Farmer Maggot has a few GDQ's them stashed in a back shed somewhere... "A-yuh... looks like the spawnin' season's almost on us... gonna be a good crop a'G<a class="nonexistent" href="./WoPs">WoPs</a> this year to take t'the market in Bree. At least those the foxes don't git first..."  <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/smile4.png" alt=";-)" height="15" width="15"> 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./MassimilianoMarangio">MassimilianoMarangio</a>: The code in question is in gen_random_quests in birth.c. Normally, a 5-10 level OOD monster is chosen, but there is a small chance of an additional boost (up to 20 level OOD). Since there are many restrictions (not a breeder, not a good monster, not a pet,...) it is possible that only a few creatures of a given level are available, resulting in repeated quests. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./RavenRed">RavenRed</a>: So if it gets that additional boost, it's a flat 20 levels, which means there's (potentially) a limited selection? That explains that. Would making it 18-20 or 15-20 fix... oh well.. it's not a major problem. After all... if it keeps Neil in GDQs... <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/smile4.png" alt=";-)" height="15" width="15"> 
</p>
<p>
Simon: Eeeeesh. 20 level out of depth critters in barrows-down level 1. This calls for a boycott of the barrows-down for a long while... 
</p>
<p>
Anyway. The lost sword backstory, as well as the princess, kinda get repetitive as storylines. We could diversify the text without changing much code functionality to get other quest types: 
</p>
<p>
FF-types: 
</p>
<p>
"I'm dying because of large kobold attacks. Arrrrgh. Avenge me!" 
</p>
<p>
"I lost a historic document right next to the large kobold. Could you get it for me?" 
</p>
<p>
"I'm an alchemist and I need my special ingredient pouch back. Please take out those eye druj for me!" 
</p>
<p>
Princess types: 
</p>
<p>
"I'm just a honest miner who dug too close to a dungeon. Please free me!" 
</p>
<p>
"Hello champion. I'm gonna test your worth by making you face my pet red dragons! Are you worthy?" 
</p>
<p>
"Please save my kitten in the tree near the Trolls! You wouldn't let a little girl down would you?" 
</p>
<p>
I'm sure you can think of better lines for them to say. The FF quest is getting OLD, and maybe FF-types should get a name and a description of his own like the princess. And saving 68 princesses is totally bogus, some of them should simply be attractive women with family connections as generated by the social class generator or something. (-; 
</p>
<p>
As I said, very little code change could go a long way here. 
</p>
<p>
Also, if we could kill FF and keep the sword (Melkor worship demands it), or charm the princess or whatever, it would mean that quests don't have very limited outcomes... I just *HATE* a princess quest when I'm all equipped... 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a>: Quest getting old?  Nobody makes you turn on 98 quests, you know.  In fact, if you do, you're probably greatly reducing your odds of winning! 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./NerdanelVampire">NerdanelVampire</a>: A percentage of all former princesses could be turned to princes just for flavor and for the benefit of straight female and gay male adventurers. Additionally, there could be crown princes and crown princesses that may appear only deep in the dungeons and give better rewards on the average than ordinary princes(ses). 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a>: RavenRed, I posted about repeated quests over on the forum some time ago... umm... probably in spoilers somewhere. Also, I think there was some discussion from others there, too, along the lines of variation on quest invitations. But anyway, who <em>doesn't</em> want a quest for 20 Great Storm Wyrms?? And another one thereafter? <em>Come to Mama,</em> I say! <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/smile4.png" alt=";)" height="15" width="15"> (And yes, I just got a second quest for Nycadaemons in Angband, oh my.) 
</p>
<p>
Nerdanel... ooooooh. Fun idea, but probably there aren't THAT many crown prince/sses around. Then again, there's probably not that many regular princess around, either, so that's not a good argument. &lt;g&gt; OTOH, I've always thought of FF as an extremely inbred Prince.... 
</p>
<p>
Bandobras: The "kitten" and "you wouldn't let a little girl down" text and the others are just wonderful! <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/biggrin.png" alt=":D" height="15" width="15"> Not that I would read them, but upon seeing a kitten inside the glass wall, I would recollect the text, and smile for the next 3 levels. <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/smile4.png" alt=";)" height="15" width="15"> Come on, people, invent some more, and let us beg the maintainers for the inclusion (I guess no module trial period would be neccesary here?). Perhaps some Tolkienian flavor there, as well?  Yeah, I get it: "you wouldn't let a little elvish girl down" --- elvish little girls possess some rather nice toys, I imagine. (comment from Simon: that would explain where junkarts come from. And change "activates for something weird" to "activates to amuse little elvish children") 
</p>
<p>
This gives me an idea of another type of quests, similar to FF. Surely someone have already suggested that: gather lost ponys (or other pets). When all the pets are within 10 squares of the player, you get a reward. If one of them dies, repeat over. Of course, a quest with nonmoving pets would be very annoying. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a>: Bandobras: the 'gathering' type of quest has already been suggested over on the forum. Well, not exactly (iirc) but there was some discussion of escorting a creature or group of creatures in order to complete the quest. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a>: It was discussed on the forum.  So? 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: So, digging around on the forum (and linking to whatever is found there) might be beneficial to this discussion. I'm not saying Bandobras' idea is a bad one. 
</p>
<p>
<strong><a href="./NeilStevens">NeilStevens</a></strong>: An impossible task, I must say.  The pathetic unsearchability of that thing is a major reason we have this wiki today, heh. 
</p>
<p>
<a href="./MassimilianoMarangio">MassimilianoMarangio</a>: Here is a partial list.  
</p>

    <ul>

    <li>
<p>
