</li>

    </ul>


<p>
<strong><a href="./MayLith">MayLith</a></strong>: MY HERO!!! <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/biggrin.png" alt=":D" height="15" width="15"> <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/biggrin.png" alt=":D" height="15" width="15"> <img src="./wiki/rightsidebar/img/biggrin.png" alt=":D" height="15" width="15"> (I think the caps are deserved, this time around. &lt;g&gt;) Seriously, there are some truly good ideas lying about rotting away in the forum, and it'd be sad to lose them. Thank you, MM! 
</p>
<p>
Simon: and if I grok the reason behind the success of the game "runescape" correctly, it's the fact that no two quests are alike or repeat at all that gave the game such a high flavor, theme, and humor. They rock! 
</p>
<p>
Some more ideas (they're coding intensive, unlike the simple "replace some text" idea which will come first because it's easy...) 
</p>
<p>
-Save the rangers from the orcs! (kill all orcs with at least half the rangers still alive). One quest maximum per "good monster" type. Can be failed. Reward a few ranger-type skills points(or novice warrior skill... etc). If you're evil you can save the orcs from the rangers and always get a warrior-type skill instead (or priest for ego Trolls). (-; 
</p>
<p>
-Find an informer: one of the humanoid monsters will not attack you, but you have no other way of knowing than looking at his behavior. Let him go next to you unharmed and he will defect! This quest is not given directly, it is a discrete part of the level feeling that becomes visible after 500 turns ("geez, so many footprints here, there must be an army hidden somewhere near!"). Reward: a bonus quest level (sort of like a death fate, but nicer because you're caught a large evil army in their sleep/drunk state - unarmored and slow!). 
</p>
<p>
-A great hero has died and his ghost wants revenge! If you succeed in killing a vault full of monsters you will gain a fate for some cool out-of-depth item. If you ignore the quest you get the weaker fate "you may be fated to die on level ..." but not "you are fated to die...". 
</p>
<p>
-You stumble upon an unstable void gate. It leads to either the top or the near-bottom of the dungeon. Jumping in might give you a corruption or kill you outright! Do you feel lucky, punk? 
</p>
<p>
-The deal: a witch wants to trade your most valuable artifact for one of his; you have 3 choices and you CAN look at the items first once you save the witch from the witch hunt, killing a few well-meaning but maybe misguided monsters. (-;  Killing her is an option, but if you do that the 3 artifacts she drops will be permacurse, aggravate, their pval lowered by 2, etc!! Say bye bye to ringil, it's been cursed by greater witchcraft!! 
</p>
<p>
-The great dragon farm has been opened by Morgoth's forces, and Eranoer the half-elf (legendary maker of dragon armors) wants you to kill all dragons and bring him one dragon corpse (of your choice) so he can make you a dragon armor for you. This will be his masterpiece before he retires ("to the great wyrm farm in the sky", he says). The dragon armor type depends on the corpse. Eranoer will appear on another level much deeper with the armor in his hands; he will give it to you and recall out. The longer you have to wait for the armor (counted in dungeon depth difference), the better the armor will be. 
</p>
<p>
-A special kind of rust affects all non-ego/artifact items on this level; it's caused by the emanations of a truly huge jelly pit. You may avoid the pit entirely, but know this: only ego and artifact items are scattered in the pit (those ego and artifact items aren't out of depth, they're calculated to be at "half depth" so the game isn't unbalanced. But hey so many ego/artifacts in the same level... whoooa!). If you leave this level, the jelly pit collapse making the level unique you can't retry later.    (hint: any player powerful enough to KNOW he can take on a giant jelly pit unprepared is not gonna find much useful here. For others it's so tempting... so dangerous. But so tempting...) 
</p>
<p>
-Elf &amp; dark elf romance: you have to go back and forth between a "romeo" and a "juliette" type monster delivering love letters, but in ToME theme(I didn't read the books - whoever did can give us theme). You must do so in a limited number of turns; failing to deliver in time twice in a row will fail the quest ("Juliette" gets an arranged wedding she doesn't like). Being in line of sight of Juliette's father counts as slower message delivery, but alas you can't kill him! Delivering in time quick enough twice in a row results in a happy wedding. Gods smile upon this wedding and you get +1d6 luck forever. Monsters appear in nonrandom patterns in the way and get tougher each time; so at some point it's wiser to let the quest fail than to get more and more out of depth monster generation here! This quest is skippable. 
</p>
<p>
-You get a fate for "an important historical relic". If you do find it (this old piece of junk will be generated once only) you get a sizeable cash reward. 
</p>
<p>
-You find a helpless kitten. Feed it and it will follow you(they DON'T eat mushrooms of unhealth or slime molds!). The "sad elvish little girl" unique is sometimes generated in town (sort of like joke monster Mathilde that "skips happily" and "waves"), and will reward you if you bring the kittens back alive. The reward is a scroll of artifact creation. After that unique is generated with a different text "happy little elvish girl". 
</p>
<p>
-Some crazy but powerful ancient mage (well, he says he's all powerful anyway) is tinkering stuff in his lab (some junkarts are in this special room - useless/bad ones - among various junk and essences). You notice an odd demonic red glowing in his eyes as well as thick red skin - a corruption no doubt! He wants to make a specific junkart power (randomly choosen) but can't quite make it, so he asks you if you have a junkart that does that. If so, you are rewarded with a junkart among 3 randomly selected nice (not overpowerful) activations. You can see in advance what they activate for. You get to name the junkart. (-; 
</p>
<p>
(spoiler: you MAY lie to him and give him just any junkart, he's too crazy to realize he's being scammed 50% of the time, but if he realizes you scammed him he will give you a heavy curse and curse-no-drop junkart of gain corruption, saying "In a century and a day, you will be able to give it to a liar. I've had it long enough, now it's YOUR TURN!"). 
</p>
<p>
-A legendary adventurer is hallulcinating badly, stuck in a small floor space surrounded by pits(or whatever makes you fall is called). There is but one patch of hallulcination-causing mushroom on the other side of the pit, easily taken care of. Your task, which will NOT be explained to you, is to get him down to less than 10 hit points so that he can be forced to quaff a potion of cure insanity(one is present - hoping the player will recognize it!). Reward: he's in your own religion(unbelievers get a nifty dark sword, non-believers get a randart), and will be able to craft the 5 god relics parts back into the original relic thru his master craftsmanship. This gives you 5 more skill point in prayer for having done all God quests; and when the relic is complete, it is an artifact which depends on which God you worship. 
</p>
<p>
Well more ideas here, but I'll wait until I see some coding to take my chances of being implemented seriously... 
</p>
